  "prompt": "How does a fluorescent light work?",
  "response": "A fluorescent light works by using electricity to excite mercury vapor, which in turn emits ultraviolet (UV) light. Here's a step-by-step explanation of the process:\n\n1. **Electric Current Activation:** When the light is turned on, an electric current flows through a pair of electrodes situated at each end of the fluorescent tube. This current passes through the inert gases (typically argon or krypton) and a small amount of mercury vapor inside the tube.\n\n2. **Excitation of Mercury Atoms:** The electric current excites the mercury atoms, causing them to emit ultraviolet (UV) photons.\n\n3. **UV Light Interaction:** The UV light emitted by the mercury atoms interacts with the phosphor coating on the inside of the fluorescent tube.\n\n4. **Phosphor Fluorescence:** The phosphor material absorbs the UV light and re-emits it as visible light. Different phosphor materials can produce different colors of light.\n\n5. **Ballast Regulation:** Fluorescent lights also use a ballast to regulate the current and provide sufficient voltage to start the lamp and then stabilize the current during operation.\n\nEssentially, the fluorescent lamp converts electrical energy into UV light through mercury vapor excitation, and then the UV light interacts with the phosphor coating to emit visible light. This process is significantly more energy-efficient compared to incandescent lamps, as it produces less heat and more light per unit of electricity consumed.",
